# Git Bash for agent shell commands (Windows)

On Windows, run **every** terminal/shell command through **Git Bash**, not raw PowerShell.

Cursor’s runner may still be PowerShell, so **wrap** Git Bash like this:

```powershell
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\bash.exe" -lc "cd '/c/Users/SumoTech-HP-840-G3/AMS' && YOUR_BASH_COMMANDS"
```

Inside the `-lc "..."` string, use **only Bash** syntax.

## Rules

- Use **bash**: `&&`, `|`, `export`, `cd`, `npm`, `git`, `ls`, `cat`, etc.
- Use **Git Bash paths**: `/c/Users/SumoTech-HP-840-G3/AMS/...` inside `-lc`.
- **Do not** use PowerShell-only syntax inside `-lc`: `Set-Location`, `$env:`, `Get-Content`, etc.
- `cd` to the repo or subfolder first, then run the command.
- Prefer commands the user can copy into their own **Git Bash** terminal (same inner string, without the `& ... -lc` wrapper if they are already in bash).

## Examples

```powershell
# Dev server
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\bash.exe" -lc "cd '/c/Users/SumoTech-HP-840-G3/AMS/frontend' && npm run dev"

# Git status
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\bash.exe" -lc "cd '/c/Users/SumoTech-HP-840-G3/AMS' && git status"
```

Copy-paste in **your** Git Bash (already in bash):

```bash
cd /c/Users/SumoTech-HP-840-G3/AMS/frontend && npm run dev
```

## User learning

When running non-obvious commands, add a short note of what the **bash** part does so the user can learn from the same commands in the integrated terminal (Git Bash profile).
